00:38.041 --> 00:46.040
Now, in the '60s and '70s the TV schedules
were awash with detective shows like The Baron,

00:46.075 --> 00:50.319
Department S, The Protectors, The
Persuaders, The Saint, The Avengers.

00:50.320 --> 00:52.519
You have no idea what
I'm talking about, do you?

00:52.520 --> 00:55.439
Let me explain.
They were all basically the same, OK?

00:55.440 --> 00:59.359
Every week a good looking man would
run into a swanky hotel, punch a

00:59.360 --> 01:03.799
swarthy looking man in a Fez and
then go to bed with a pretty lady.

01:03.834 --> 01:07.158
Anyone here old enough to
remember that? Yeah, you, exactly.

01:07.159 --> 01:11.718
The only difference was
the cars they all drove, OK?

01:11.719 --> 01:14.758
This is Brett Sinclair,
Aston Martin DBS.

01:14.759 --> 01:17.398
Steed had a Broadspeed tuned Jag.

01:17.399 --> 01:22.358
And there is The Saint with his Volvo P1800.

01:22.359 --> 01:25.963
Now, the interesting thing is
that almost none of them ever drove

01:25.998 --> 01:30.958
the Jensen Interceptor, and I think
there's a very good reason for that.

01:35.838 --> 01:43.278
It looks fantastic, but it was built very badly by
people who didn't seem to care what they were doing.

01:46.117 --> 01:48.996
Let me give you one example.

01:48.997 --> 01:52.996
When the people on the Jensen production
line needed a new steering rack they'd go to

01:52.997 --> 01:59.196
the steering rack factory and buy one, often
without bothering to check what car it was for.

01:59.197 --> 02:05.757
Some Interceptors were apparently sold fitted
with steering racks designed for the Triumph Stag.

02:07.316 --> 02:12.595
That, then, is why it wasn't
very popular with the TV heroes of yesteryear.

02:12.596 --> 02:15.476
It would never have worked properly.

02:20.436 --> 02:24.715
Now, though, a small company
based here in the lungs of England

02:24.750 --> 02:29.555
has launched an updated version,
which does.

02:37.395 --> 02:41.754
In the old car the big Chrysler
engine turned petrol into noise,

02:41.755 --> 02:44.559
but very little power was produced on the way,

02:44.594 --> 02:48.314
so they've taken that
engine out and thrown it away.

02:51.194 --> 02:56.073
In its place there's a 6.2 litre
V8 from the modern day Corvette.

02:56.074 --> 03:00.673
The rear suspension is modern, too,
as are the brakes.

03:00.674 --> 03:07.193
But, critically, the body, that glorious
Italian styling, that's untouched.

03:07.228 --> 03:10.633
And it still has the best name
ever put on a car...

03:11.713 --> 03:12.953
Interceptor.

03:18.993 --> 03:22.592
So, what we have here then is much
the same as that house over there.

03:22.593 --> 03:29.032
It's old and it's beautiful, but it has central
heating, it has all the appurtenances of modern living.

03:29.067 --> 03:35.471
And unlike that modern day E type we looked
at the other day this doesn't cost £500,000.

03:35.472 --> 03:37.512
This is £112,000.

03:39.032 --> 03:43.631
I know that's a lot if you're on benefits,
but it's not a lot if you're on Elton John.

03:43.632 --> 03:45.996
I mean, if you are Elton John.

03:46.031 --> 03:50.751
And it's really not a lot when
you see what this car can do.

03:54.071 --> 04:00.190
Thanks to 429 horsepower, 0 to 60 is
dealt with in 4.5 seconds

04:00.191 --> 04:05.030
and the top speed is 167.

04:05.031 --> 04:10.190
It goes, then, like that other
interceptor from the period,

04:10.225 --> 04:12.989
the English Electric Lightning.

04:12.990 --> 04:16.428
However, it as thirsty as the jet,

04:16.430 --> 04:18.310
and as noisy.

04:19.550 --> 04:25.589
The engine in this, though,
sounds fantastic... I think.

04:25.590 --> 04:28.429
It's hard to be sure because there's
so much wind noise

04:28.464 --> 04:31.108
coming from here and everywhere else.

04:31.109 --> 04:35.868
It's a reminder, really, that this
car was built in the '70s

04:35.869 --> 04:38.388
in the West Midlands and these words,

04:38.389 --> 04:43.469
"West", "Seventies", "Midlands,"
they're not bywords for quality.

04:45.109 --> 04:49.308
There are other period features
I don't much care for either.

04:49.343 --> 04:52.307
First of all there's the air
conditioning. Two settings,

04:52.308 --> 04:54.787
sauna or Turkish prison.

04:54.788 --> 05:01.107
Then you've got the wipers, which are as good at
removing water from the windscreen as a pair of pencils.

05:01.108 --> 05:03.347
And then there's the steering system.

05:03.348 --> 05:07.307
It's original, so it could be from
a Triumph Stag or it could be from

05:07.342 --> 05:09.586
a lawn mower, who knows?

05:09.587 --> 05:13.746
What I do know is to make the car
move that much

05:13.747 --> 05:17.547
you have to do quite a lot
of flailing at the wheel.

05:19.227 --> 05:23.506
There are, however, some
period features I love.

05:23.507 --> 05:28.146
The traditional white on black dials are
the sort you get in war films, that you tap

05:28.181 --> 05:31.625
when they tell you bad news
and then they tell you good news.

05:31.626 --> 05:33.185
Oh no, I've got no fuel!

05:33.186 --> 05:36.065
Oh, look, I've got a full tank!

05:36.066 --> 05:40.745
I also like having the
dim dip switch on the floor.

05:40.746 --> 05:43.545
And, look at that radio!

05:43.546 --> 05:46.145
'This is the BBC Home Service. '

05:46.146 --> 05:49.226
It's from the James May collection.

05:50.825 --> 05:53.464
So, how do we sum this car up?

05:53.465 --> 05:56.864
Certainly it's more of a
grand tourer than a raging

05:56.865 --> 06:02.024
B road barnstormer, but I
think that what it is most of all

06:02.025 --> 06:04.384
is a time machine.

06:04.385 --> 06:09.824
In my head, right now this is not
Top Gear and this is not 2011.

06:09.859 --> 06:16.743
It's 1972, I have an enormous
moustache and I am the star

06:16.744 --> 06:19.064
of a new TV detective show.

06:28.464 --> 06:30.548
Nice wheels.

06:30.583 --> 06:33.942
Rock your head. I would have done
if you'd gone within a metre of me!

06:33.943 --> 06:36.502
I did! It was like
you're swatting a fly over there.

06:36.503 --> 06:38.341
That was rubbish. Did you see that?

06:38.342 --> 06:39.463
Yeah, it was rubbish.

06:39.464 --> 06:42.542
We can't just go around
pretending to punch each other.

06:42.543 --> 06:47.742
You need a sort of proper sequence. Nice wheels,
by the way. Isn't it just the best thing ever?

06:47.743 --> 06:49.588
We need to sort this out.
We need a plan.

06:49.623 --> 06:56.941
So, we adjourned to the Top Gear office
to plan our Interceptor tribute show.

06:56.942 --> 07:01.821
Why don't we just make the title sequence?
Title sequence is a good idea because

07:01.822 --> 07:05.701
that tells the whole story. It sums up
the atmosphere and the setting. Exactly.

07:05.702 --> 07:08.981
They're always very short and
they often end with a freeze.

07:08.982 --> 07:11.346
Yeah, exactly.
And everyone turns like that.

07:11.381 --> 07:14.300
And there's always somebody
doing karate chops on people.

07:14.301 --> 07:18.500
No, there's always a karate chop,
shooting, car chase. Explosion.

07:18.501 --> 07:20.061
